A few important implementation notes I baked into the document:

Next.js App Router is used as the frontend foundation. Next.js documents App Router as the newer router for modern React features.
Prisma ORM + PostgreSQL is used for the database layer; Prisma’s docs describe Prisma ORM as open-source and type-safe for Node.js/TypeScript apps.
For OTP/passwordless auth, I aligned the design around an open-source-first approach using a passwordless pattern that supports one-time codes via email/phone flows. SuperTokens documents passwordless auth using OTP or magic links and supports email/SMS behavior customization.
For subscriptions, the architecture uses a provider abstraction, with Stripe as the recommended adapter because Stripe Billing supports recurring subscriptions and Checkout-based subscription flows well.

One practical note: I also added your requirement that the app should be open-source first, but for real production phone OTP and payment processing, you will usually still need an external delivery/provider layer. The document handles that by using adapter interfaces so you can plug in Stripe/Razorpay, SMTP, or SMS gateways without locking the platform to one vendor.

